This is Daryl Lane and David Carson collecting is a hobby or an obsession that
many people engage in. Coins, stamps, antiques, people collect almost anything and

00:50.960 --> 00:58.120
science fiction fans are certainly no exception. There are a fair number of
science fiction collectors scattered around some are so called completists who

00:58.120 --> 01:04.900
accumulate anything related to the field while others concentrate on a
particular thing. Many science fiction collectors for example collect books

01:04.900 --> 01:11.940
either paperbacks or hardbacks or magazines having to do with science fiction or
fantasy. The Science Fiction Radio Show spoke with two serious collectors

01:11.940 --> 01:19.240
recently each with a different background in a different area of interest. The
first is John Marks, a chemistry professor at Texas Tech University in Lubbock,

01:19.240 --> 01:27.120
Texas. The second is Bob Wayne, the owner of fantastic worlds bookstore in Fort
Worth, Texas. We asked Bob Wayne what kind of science fiction material he collects.

01:27.120 --> 01:39.980
At this time my main collections I'm collecting things by Philip Jose Farmer
Michael Moorcock and Harlan Ellison and so i just concentrate you know

01:39.980 --> 01:48.540
essentially on finding things that i don't already have and i work off of
bibliographies and lists and try to find things are in in better condition than

01:48.540 --> 01:59.660
the ones i already have so looking for for for hardcover books that are you know
where they're published in small quantities and looking for paperback books that

01:59.660 --> 02:09.140
are published under pseudonyms or from small presses or the things that require
the most attention for finding them at inexpensive prices. John Marks goes about

02:09.140 --> 02:19.380
it a little differently. i started out with paperbacks and uh the digest
magazines i've gone back in uh terms of get it picking up the old pulp magazines

02:19.380 --> 02:29.120
to the point where now i have almost all of them that were ever published
starting back with Weird Tales in 1923 and Amazing Stories in 1926 i'm very

02:29.120 --> 02:39.100
proud of my complete collection of weird tales since i understand there's only
about 30 copies or so in existence and uh just about as good on astounding

02:39.100 --> 02:50.660
science fiction for example. Recently i have been branching out into hardbacks
also but i'm a long long ways from complete on that what about paperbacks well i

02:50.660 --> 03:01.080
have about 14, 15 000 is that enough for you we asked john marks if he picks up
all paperbacks or just certain kinds there's always a problem in making the

03:01.080 --> 03:11.080
where do you draw the line but i basically get everything that's clearly science
fiction um everything that's clearly fantasy i kind of draw the line someplace

03:11.080 --> 03:21.940
in the horror vein to one side and maybe fairy tales on the other side and uh
sometimes i'll draw the line at uh you know uh an atom bomb story that's setting

03:21.940 --> 03:32.480
them near future or something like that but basically i get every hard every
paperback in science fiction and fantasy. We asked Wayne what he would advise a

03:32.480 --> 03:40.060
reader who wanted to turn collector well first thing i would do obviously a
person is going to come in and say i want to start collecting has already read

03:40.060 --> 03:48.800
some stuff so i would say to them what have you read so far give me the name of
some authors that you've enjoyed some books that you've liked. I would

03:48.800 --> 03:59.540
springboard off of that to pointing out things that i would feel there would be
you know good collectible books within their field of interest so that was how

03:59.540 --> 04:08.280
you know i would handle that particular situation. We asked Marks the same
question and he had much the same answer. Probably what most people will do when

04:08.280 --> 04:18.060
they start is they will pick a favorite author or authors and try to get all the
books by that person somebody with a limited budget just starting think you know

04:18.060 --> 04:26.500
that's it's a pretty good first step to say for example get every book a copy of
some edition of every book that Robert A. Heinlein has written or Andre Norton

04:26.500 --> 04:36.440
or or you name it whoever whoever the person happens to like and uh once they do
that and if they if they start getting the collecting bug then pretty soon

04:36.440 --> 04:45.400
they'll want to trade in those later printings for first editions and uh then if
they've really gotten into it they'll want to trade in those first beat up first

04:45.400 --> 04:53.540
editions for better first copies of the first editions when they do it they'll
probably start expanding into into other authors, More on collecting on our next

04:53.540 --> 04:53.820
show.

