This is David Carson. And Daryl Lane. We are talking with two collectors of
science fiction books, John Marks, a chemistry professor at Texas Tech

06:40.960 --> 06:48.520
University, and Bob Wayne, owner of the Fantastic Worlds bookstore in Fort
Worth, Texas. We asked Bob Wayne what makes a book valuable, a collectible item.

06:49.160 --> 06:58.940
Well, from the simplest standpoint, what makes a hardback book collectible to
anyone is simply supply and demand, and that there are more people wanting the

06:58.940 --> 07:08.300
book than there are books available at cover price. Usually this doesn't take
place, obviously, until after the book is out of print. But oftentimes, science

07:08.300 --> 07:17.880
fiction fans will see a hardcover book and they'll say, hmm, well, if I wait a
year, I can buy that in paperback. And they'll pass the book up. And then when

07:17.880 --> 07:24.140
the book comes out in paperback, they read it and discover it's the greatest
thing since they put raisins in bread. So they go back and they want to buy it

07:24.140 --> 07:31.520
in hardcover for a durable copy. However, at this time, the publisher has
probably already either remaindered the book or allowed the book to go out of

07:31.520 --> 07:39.360
print when all the copies were sold by the people who did buy it in hardcover.
And the supply of people out there looking for the book and demanding, I want a

07:39.360 --> 07:49.100
copy of book X, and no books being available, forces the price up on the
collector's market. The other things that can cause a book to become valuable

07:49.100 --> 08:00.180
are usually errors in the same way that a stamp being printed upside down would
cause a stamp to be valuable. If a publisher decides to accidentally destroy all

08:00.180 --> 08:10.580
the copies of a book so that only a few hundred exist, or if only a few copies
are made with some variation that was corrected in another edition, this also

08:10.580 --> 08:20.080
can cause a book to be valuable. And then you also can have a situation where
you create a book just to make a book valuable. That would be the case whenever

08:20.080 --> 08:28.580
you have a strictly limited edition where it's signed and numbered. What would a
real prize be for the collector of hardback science fiction books? John Marks

08:28.580 --> 08:38.240
answers this one. Well, it depends on what you're talking about. For example,
here's an example a lot of people would know about. Frank Herbert's Dune,

08:38.440 --> 08:47.680
hardcover the first edition, is worth a great, great deal of money simply
because Dune wasn't that well known when it first came out, didn't attract that

08:47.680 --> 08:59.720
much attention until slowly over several years, and that first hardcover edition
is extremely hard to find. So that in good condition, I understand that a first

08:59.720 --> 09:07.940
edition is worth a thousand bucks. Well, I don't have a copy of it. I wouldn't
mind having a copy at all, although I wouldn't pay that money for it. But I know

09:07.940 --> 09:17.720
somebody who found one in the garage sale in Lubbock. That bugs the heck out of
me. It wasn't me. We asked Marks how much a valuable science fiction paperback

09:17.720 --> 09:28.340
might be worth. Well, I could tell you the highest price I've heard anybody
charge for anything, and that was, and I don't know that they got it, this was

09:28.340 --> 09:41.360
the asking price, was $175 for Cat in a Canary House by Kurt Vonnegut. And that
book, which is his only collection of short stories and which are all

09:41.360 --> 09:49.960
unabashedly science fiction, he vows he'll never allow reprints as long as he
lives, and there aren't all that many copies available, so the price of that

09:49.960 --> 09:58.140
thing has been really escalating. I got my copy for $3, I don't mind telling
you. With such prices for single books, collecting seems to be a good

09:58.140 --> 10:07.700
investment. We asked John Marks if it was. My advice to somebody who wants to do
that is you've got to know a heck of a lot about this field before you're likely

10:07.700 --> 10:18.800
to be very successful at it, going about it from that standpoint, because just
because something is old doesn't necessarily mean that it's especially valuable.

10:19.080 --> 10:27.720
And what's real, it would be really difficult from the investor's standpoint,
from somebody who knew very little about the field, is to know which books to

10:27.720 --> 10:36.100
pick up now because 10 years from now they're going to be worth a lot. In fact,
that's kind of hard for me to guess. And I certainly know more about it than a

10:36.100 --> 10:39.740
lot of people do. We'll continue with the subject of collecting on our next
show.

