12:21.820 --> 12:27.740
John Marks a professor of chemistry at Texas Tech University in Lubbock, Texas. His
passion is collecting science fiction books and magazines, and he has many

12:27.740 --> 12:37.220
thousands of them. We asked him if he had an area of concentration in his
collecting. Well, I once gave a talk on this subject, and I titled it The

12:37.220 --> 12:50.560
Complete Science Fiction Collector, Confessions of a Pack Rat. In other words,
I'm very, very versatile and dabbling in my tastes. I don't like all kinds of

12:50.560 --> 13:02.240
things equally, but I collect anything that's published in the science fiction
and fantasy vein, I get my hands on, and then I can afford. Which means almost,

13:02.380 --> 13:13.820
I've got copies of almost every book that's been published. Why does John Marks
collect science fiction books? What's the fascination? Because it's there? Sure.

13:15.000 --> 13:23.200
That's actually, I suppose, a difficult question for anyone to answer. First of
all, you have to love books, or whatever you're collecting. I mean, this is the

13:23.200 --> 13:36.980
collector's mania. There's lots of people that collect anything from matchbooks
to old Avon bottles, for heaven's sakes. And I collect what I enjoy from other

13:36.980 --> 13:47.760
standpoints. I enjoy the artwork on them. I enjoy reading the things. I like to
read at least a representative book by any author that's important in the field,

13:47.780 --> 13:58.680
and so on. And I just love books. I love to handle them. I love to sort them,
catalog them, put them away, just look at them. And that's what I do with a fair

13:58.680 --> 14:09.240
portion of my spare time, I guess. But why collect science fiction books? Why
not coins or stamps or seashells? Because I love science fiction. Something we

14:09.240 --> 14:22.300
haven't gotten into the conversation yet is, here at Texas Tech, I also am
involved in helping the team teach the course in science fiction. We have a

14:22.300 --> 14:33.020
special course through our honors program, and there are three or four of us
every semester team teach this thing to a small group, and we try to teach them

14:33.020 --> 14:41.740
principles about writing also, so it's a creative writing course, very much a
discussion course, and so on. But I just love science fiction. I don't mind

14:41.740 --> 14:50.440
reading an occasional mystery, let's say. I haven't read a Western in 20 years,
but I've read lots of science fiction. Since that's what I like to read, that's

14:50.440 --> 15:00.980
what I like to collect. Also, I might say that many of the older science fiction
books are more valuable to collectors in general than many of those in other

15:00.980 --> 15:12.300
fields of, say, comparable age and publisher. We asked Marks which part of his
collection he's most proud of. My pulp magazines, I think, is sort of my own

15:12.300 --> 15:21.620
favorite among all the things. You know, people come into the house, visitors
that know nothing about science fiction, and I always trot them downstairs and

15:21.620 --> 15:31.860
show them the collection. Kind of funny to watch somebody, you hand them one of
those old pulp magazines, give them one that isn't crumbling too badly, and then

15:31.860 --> 15:39.960
they start looking at all the old ads from the 30s or whatever. It's kind of a
history lesson just to go through the things if they don't know the stories or

15:39.960 --> 15:50.300
care about that especially, why they find the ads more fascinating than
anything. But I started out in the terms of serious collecting with the

15:50.300 --> 16:01.760
magazines and the pulp especially, and those early ones especially are, there
just aren't very many copies around, and so that's kind of my favorite part of

16:01.760 --> 16:13.180
the collection. Would he sell his collection for a high enough price? Probably
not now. I do know somebody who retired and took a round-the-world trip on

16:13.180 --> 16:21.440
selling his. In the area John Marks concentrates on, paperbacks, pulps, and
magazines, he doubts there are many collections in the country except for

16:21.440 --> 16:22.660
libraries that surpass his.

