23:41.880 --> 23:49.540
This is Daryl Lane. And David Carson. Older readers and fans of science fiction
may be bewildered at what's happened to their field today. Science fiction is

23:49.540 --> 23:56.940
not found only in books and movies anymore. It's spilled over into role-playing
games like Dungeons & Dragons and into numerous video games for home television

23:56.940 --> 24:04.300
and computers. The market for materials related to these games is tremendous,
but so is the market for traditional science fiction books and magazines. Bob

24:04.300 --> 24:11.360
Wayne, owner of Fantastic Worlds Bookstore in Fort Worth, Texas, supplies
customers in both areas. We asked him to tell us about Fantastic Worlds.

24:12.480 --> 24:23.900
Fantastic Worlds Bookstore, the store that I own, started off, you know, two and
a half years ago. And we specialize in items of the fantastic. We have comic

24:23.900 --> 24:33.440
books, science fiction books, fantasy role-playing games, video games, and
science fiction movies on videotape. And all the other paraphernalia that you

24:33.440 --> 24:43.060
would expect in relation to those items. For example, lead miniatures for role
-playing games or dice. We have comics, bags to put comics in, boxes, posters,

24:43.340 --> 24:55.980
portfolios, movie posters. Just an assortment of things, you know, related. We
go all the way from talking animals like Garfield to Superman to Doctor Who and

24:55.980 --> 25:05.500
to Felix the Cat. Just a wide variety of things. All, the only common element is
that they're all science fiction, fantasy concepts to some extent.

25:14.860 --> 25:23.360
Wayne also collects both comics and science fiction hardbacks. We asked him to
tell us how he began his collection. The way I got started in collecting is

25:23.360 --> 25:35.260
actually the way I got started in reading. My paternal grandfather was a bus
driver. He used to pick up comic books that people left on the bus and bring

25:35.260 --> 25:43.060
them, you know, and I would get them from him. So I learned how to read when I
was about five years old by reading comic books that were left on buses. So

25:43.060 --> 25:55.600
everyone who rode on a bus through much of Texas in 1959, 1958, 1960, you know,
I'm in their debt for being able to read from an early age and for my love of

25:55.600 --> 26:05.660
comics and science fiction. And I went from that to keeping the comics that I
had read and putting them on a little shelf in my closet. And from that point,

26:05.720 --> 26:15.780
it began to snowball where, you know, I began picking up anything that I felt
was related to comics. And then I eventually got into science fiction reading

26:15.780 --> 26:25.080
when I met Fritz Leiber at a convention in 1968. Wayne says his collection led
into his becoming the founder and proprietor of Fantastic Worlds. He tells us

26:25.080 --> 26:36.780
how that happened. At one point, you know, I noticed that my personal taste in
comic books, the ones that I felt were the superior examples of comic books as

26:36.780 --> 26:47.460
an art, and the ones that seemed to be increasing in value on the collector's
market, had a lot in common. And I began to feel that there was the potential

26:47.460 --> 26:55.360
that if I picked up a couple of extra copies of the ones that I felt were really
good comics, that they would appreciate in value faster than just going in and

26:55.360 --> 27:06.660
buying a handful at random. And so I began to speculate in comic books by buying
them on the hope that someone would come along later and want to pay me more

27:06.660 --> 27:16.640
money for them than I had paid for them myself. And then I began to do the same
thing with science fiction books, but on the smaller margin. I began buying

27:16.640 --> 27:26.720
books from England, which were not generally available in this country in the
late 70s, and taking them to conventions and selling those. And I kept sending

27:26.720 --> 27:37.260
aside more and more extra comics and more and more books. And I realized that I
had to either buy myself a larger house to store all this stuff in than I was

27:37.260 --> 27:46.860
only using a couple of times a year, or going ahead and open a store for
retailing. I chose to open a store, you know, because this has much more tax

27:46.860 --> 27:49.280
advantages to owning a house just to store books in.

